### Setup
- Neo4j OGM 3.2.31
- In Process Neo4j 4.4.4 Enterprise (with BOLT port exposed)
- Spring Boot 2.6.4
- Spring Data Neo4j 5.3.9.RELEASE (connected using [this example](https://github.com/michael-simons/neo4j-from-the-jvm-ecosystem/tree/41e0fded281a71758263d1924a85eede72e00f70/spring-boot26-with-sdn-ogm))

### Issue
I'm persisting an object using `session.save`. Afterwards I'm loading the same entity using `session.queryForObject`.
The entity I'm persisting has an `Instant` attribute that is annotated with `@DateLong`. Java Instant has microsecond precision whilst `@DateLong` stores it only with millisecond precision. However if I'm executing `session.queryForObject` within the same transaction/session, OGM returns the exact same java object that I passed to `session.save` before and therefor I don't get the data that's actually stored in the database.
One could argue that converters should always be bijections but then I would argue that `@DateLong` needs to be deprecated with a clear warning.

A similar/worse issue happens in the following application flow (pseudo code):
```java
X x = new X();
x.setFirstName("Foo");
session.save(x);
session.query("MATCH (n) SET n.firstName = $name", Collections.singletonMap("name", "bar"));
X x2 = session.queryForObject(X.class, "MATCH (n{firstName:$name}) RETURN n", Collections.singletonMap("name", "bar"));
// now I get an x2 but it is actually x1 and has name "Foo"
```

