@cbeams [wrote](https://github.com/bisq-network/roles/issues/18#issuecomment-1097807082):

> I've just re-enabled Cloudflare proxying in front of the bisq.network site [...] because there was what looks like an attack [...] totaling nearly a TB of data transfer. [...] I see no practical downside in doing this, and the change is easy to reverse (to remove the proxying) if anything does come up.

@wiz wrote:

> I'm just commenting to object to hosting bisq.network behind Cloudflare - it's basically a NSA choke point and MITM as a service - if you really need DoS filtering there are way better options

I'd prefer we didn't front with CF as well, even if only on principle. However, we did have an attack and fronting with CF is a simple and easily reversible prophylactic measure. Assuming CF does get used as a choke point to shut down access to the Bisq website in the future, we'd just disable the proxying. If CF simultaneously denied our account access, we'd just change the DNS records at the registrar. The only way a such a choke point operation would cause any sustained damage is if there were also a simultaneous DDoS so overwhelming that the hosting provider shut down the app instead of simply billing us for the increased traffic like they did before.

With that said, I currently see fronting with CF as low-risk effective protection. If there's a drop-in replacement for CF that further improves the risk/reward ratio and better aligns with Bisq's decentralization principles, I'm all ears. What's your proposal?

events.body:
I'm not sure about the name just yet, but we should have a `SessionRepository` implementation that can ignore specific set of exceptions to allow ignoring of deserialization exceptions (i.e. when a serialization UID changes). The implementation would look something like this, but would either allow for customizing the exceptions that are ignored or we would require updates to the existing implementations to ensure that they threw a consistent exception if deserialization failed (perfered):

``` java
public class SafeDeserializingSessionRepository<S extends ExpiringSession> implements SessionRepository<S> {
    private final SessionRepository<S> repository;

    public SafeDeserializingSessionRepository(SessionRepository<S> repository) {
        this.repository = repository;
    }

    public S getSession(String id) {
        try {
            return repository.getSession(id);
        } catch(SerializationException e) {
            delete(id);
            return null;
        }
    }

    public S createSession() {
        return repository.createSession();
    }

    public void save(S session) {
        repository.save(session);
    }

    public void delete(String id) {
        repository.delete(id);
    }
}
```

